            "answer_text": "A pair of electrons which do not take part in bond formation in a molecule is called lone pair. Let's take an example of a water(H2O) molecule. A oxygen molecule when form a covalent bond with two two hydrogen atoms then a water molecule is formed.  As we know that oxygen has 6 valence electrons in it's outermost orbit therefore to complete it's octet it needs two electrons which are provided by two hydrogen atoms by forming covalent bond with it. Now the electrons which do not took part \u200bin the bond formation viz. two pair of electrons, are called lone pairs of oxygen atom in water molecule. ",
